            <p>New York July 15&#47;88.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. D<hi rend="sup">r</hi> S. Morais <hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi>.<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>On the strength of the enclosed I have<lb/> ventured at the eleventh hour to trouble you with<lb/> the following&#44; hoping you will pardon me for<lb/> being the cause of inconvenience to you.&#45;&#45;<lb/> The cause of my troubling you is simply<lb/> this&#58; I have been bedridden the whole of<lb/> last winter with Rheumatism&#44; and my<lb/> precarious livelihood&#44; teaching&#44; has thus failed<lb/> to support me during that time on account<lb/> of weakness&#44; which still clings to me&#44; and<lb/> prevents me from visiting Ph. in person.&#45;<lb/> Being advanced in years the fervent prayer<lb/> of the royal Psalmist&#58; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> seems to be hard upon me&#44; and &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> I sincerely beg of you&#44; to oblige the bearer of this&#44;<lb/> my son&#44; with a few <hi rend="underline">good names</hi> of your congregations<lb/> where he may have a chance to sell <hi rend="underline">a few copies</hi>&#44;<lb/> to help me a little under present difficulties.  By<lb/> so doing you will oblige to an everlasting obligation<lb/> Yours respectfully&#44; Hy. Abarbanel.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
